\description{
With the two-phase discovery, the probe scans all rows before resolving the schema.  Variant-B's \verb{x = Some(42u64)} contributes a \code{Scalar(Real)} candidate which beats the \code{Scalar(Generic)} from variant-A's \code{x = None}.  The column ends up as a numeric vector with \code{NA} in row 1.

Two-phase discovery: \code{Compound} candidate from row 2 beats \code{Scalar(Generic)} from row 1.  Result: columns \code{point_x} and \code{point_y}, with NA in row 1.

Two-phase discovery: the \code{Scalar(Real)} candidate from row 2 beats \code{Scalar(Generic)} from row 1.  Result: numeric column with NA at index 1.

When every row is \code{None}, the probe never sees any struct fields, so struct expansion never fires.  The entire \code{point} field becomes a single logical NA column under the field name \code{"point"} — not per-subfield \code{"point_x"}/\code{"point_y"}.

Rows alternate between variant A (has \code{value} only) and variant B (has \code{value} and \code{extra}).  The \code{extra} field only appears in B rows; \code{value} appears in both. Because both rows contribute scalar candidates for \code{value}, the first non-Generic wins.  The schema discovers both \code{value} and \code{extra} fields (from their respective rows) because they are distinct keys — they are \emph{not} the same compound key.

Rows: None, None, Some(42u64), None.  Two-phase discovery resolves the column to \code{Scalar(Real)}.  Result: numeric column with NA at positions 1, 2, 4.
